    "title": "Studies",
    "description": "Shorter meditations on paintings, images, and recurring visual obsessions.",
    "content": "These pieces are smaller in scale, but not minor. I think of them as studies in the old sense of the word: attempts to stay with a single image long enough for it to stop being decorative and become diagnostic.\n\nMost of them begin with a painting and remain close to it. Instead of building a full argument, they try to register a pressure: a posture, a color, a silence, a historical contradiction, a mood that refuses to dissolve.\n\nGood places to start:\n\n- [The Fortune Teller](/paintings/caravaggio-the-fortune-teller-1594)\n- [The Soothsayer's Recompense](/paintings/giorgio-de-chirico-the-soothsayers-recompense-1913)\n- [The Cyclops](/paintings/odilon-redon-the-cyclops-1914)\n- [The Bolshevik and the Weight of an Idea](/paintings/boris-kustodiev-the-bolshevik-1920)\n- [Adele Bloch-Bauer I](/paintings/gustav-klimt-adele-bloch-bauer-I)\n- [The Demon Seated](/paintings/vrubel-demon-1890)\n\nIf you want the longer argumentative pieces where these images open into essays, go to [Essays](/essays).",
